Introduction

The COVID-19 pandemic has generated enormous media response in Switzerland. Since its onset in March 2020, a considerable bulk of coverage has been produced by Swiss media companies to spread information about the new virus and its impact on health, economic activity and social interaction in the whole country.

In communication studies, it is suggested that different media types show different levels of journalistic quality. Previous analysis have shown, that the tabloiod press as well as printed press that is distributed freely (e.g.Â commuter press) tend to put more emphasis on a emotionalized style of reporting in order to gain more attention and hence be more attractive to advertisers.

In this paper, I will thus engage in sheding light on the media coverage in Switzerland as the COVID-19 pandemic unfolded, in particular with a focus on the emotionalization of journalistic content. For this purpose, I will analyse texts that have been produced for printed media types such as subscription newspapers, commuter news, the tabloid press and magazines in printed form and online contents as well as news from public broadcasting websites with respect to their degree of emotionalization.

Furthermore, I will investigate how user interacted with online coverage of the COVID-19 pandemic by commenting on articles and by reacting to comments with hits on love/hate buttons. For this purpose, all articles, the most prominent comments and the user reactions to the comments have beed scraped from the watson.ch newspage.

In the subsequent analysis, chunks of R code can be obtained from the respective collapsed sections labelled âShow codeâ by clicking on the arrow.

News Coverage of the COVID-19 Pandemic in Switzerland

Data: Retrieval, Sampling and Preprocessing

The data for media analysis was collected from Swissdox@LiRI. This repository collects articles of all Swiss printed and online press sources as well as transcripts from some public broadcasting programs. For the purpose of this analysis, the database was searched for all articles dating from the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic in March 2020 until the date of the query at June 4th 2022. The following keywords were used to specify the search: covid, corona, Covid, Corona, covid*, corona*, Covid*, Corona* in order to ensure the inclusion of all relevant articles in german, french, italian and rhaeto-romanic language. This request resulted in a query including 1â128â420, of which 1% was randomly selected to produce a sample of 11â284 articles. This sample dataset was saved and will be used for the subsequent analysis.
Show R code 
## ORIGINAL DATA
df <- read_tsv(file = '1b4bcb1e-d578-4ce3-bc74-b9f3362b1600__2022_06_04T12_55_03.tsv')
# random sampling 1%: 11'284 of 1'128'420
set.seed(1234)
dat <- slice_sample(df, n=11284, replace = F)
dat <- distinct(dat, content_id, .keep_all = T) #11089 from 11284
saveRDS(dat, "sample mediadata 11284.RDS")


In a first step, the data was cleaned from HTML-tags; furthermore rhaeto-romanic articles were eliminated from the sample due to missing dictionaries for further text-analysis as well as articles in the english language because they cannot be attributed to a linguistic region unambiguously. This reduced the original sample from 11â284 to 11â032 articles. Additional date-variables for day, week and month were included to facilitate aggregation.

Medium Type

Although the original dataset contains variables for the type of document, the most prominent category of âOnline mediumâ referred merely to the availability of articles on an online platform regardlessof the media title and therefore contained articles from subscription and tabloid press as well as freely available content of sources such as commuter press. This categorization did not turn out to be useful for further analysis. All media titles in the sample were thus sorted into categories, most of which were collected from fÃ¶gâs âJahrbuch QualitÃ¤t der Medienâ (p.Â 144). Media titles that could not be retrieved from the aforementioned source were categorized according to their specific characteristics gathered by online research. These categories include subscriptions (payed journals), commuter press (free journals), tabloid press, magazines (illustrated press) and SRG Online (Switzerlandâs public broadcasting news). All of these categories were subdivided into printed and online ressources except for SRG Online, which is of course available online only.

Topwords

For further processing the data was split into a separate dataset for each language. As a preparation for text-analysis, corpi were constructed, tokenized, decapitalized, cleaned and stemmed. No compound word elimination was conducted because of several reasons: In the german language, compound words are usually written as one word or connected with a dash. Furthermore, an initial inspection of the topwords ordered by their frequency has shown no obvious terms that needed to be merged. Finally, a document-feature-matrix was generated for each language.
Show R code 
# split into languages
dat_de <- dat[dat$language=="de",]
dat_fr <- dat[dat$language=="fr",]
dat_it <- dat[dat$language=="it",]

corp_de <- corpus(dat_de, text_field = "content")
corp_fr <- corpus(dat_fr, text_field = "content")
corp_it <- corpus(dat_it, text_field = "content")

tok_de <- tokens(corp_de, 
                 remove_separators = TRUE,
                 remove_numbers = TRUE,
                 include_docvars = TRUE,
                 remove_punct = T)
tok_fr <- tokens(corp_fr,
                 remove_separators = TRUE,
                 remove_numbers = TRUE,
                 include_docvars = TRUE,
                 remove_punct = T)
tok_it <- tokens(corp_it,
                 remove_separators = TRUE,
                 remove_numbers = TRUE,
                 include_docvars = TRUE,
                 remove_punct = T)

tok_de <- tok_de %>% 
  tokens_tolower %>%  
  tokens_remove(stopwords(kind = "german"), padding = TRUE) %>% 
  tokens_wordstem(language = "german") %>%
  tokens_remove("")
# iterative elimination
tok_de <- tokens_remove(tok_de, c("dass", "sei", "seit", "imm", "ab", "beim", "+", "frank"))

tok_fr <- tok_fr %>% 
  tokens_tolower %>% 
  tokens_remove(stopwords(kind = "french"), padding = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_wordstem(language = "french") %>%
  tokens_remove("")
# iterative elimination
tok_fr <- tokens_remove(tok_fr, c("a", "d'un", "c'est", "comm", "deux", "auss", "si", "qu'il", "Ãªtre", "n'est", "selon", "autr", "oÃ¹", "s'est", "alor", "dÃ©jÃ ", "dont"))

tok_it <- tok_it %>% 
  tokens_tolower %>% 
  tokens_remove(stopwords(kind = "italian"), padding = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_wordstem(language = "italian") %>%
  tokens_remove("")
# iterative elimination
tok_it <- tokens_remove(tok_it, c("due", "sol", "second", "dett", "far", "alcun"))

dfm_de <- dfm(tok_de)
dfm_fr <- dfm(tok_fr)
dfm_it <- dfm(tok_it)

Rubrics

The original dataset included also a variable for the rubric of an article. The categories for this variable were chosen arbitrarily by the media companies and are therefore not suitable for analysis. Furthermore, a large proportion of values were missing (3â104 from 11â032 articles = 28%) and a large part of the remaining categories consisted more of headlines than actual rubric categories. To construct a variable with a valid categorization of the articlesâ rubrics, a supervised machine learning algorithm was adopted. As a preparation, the available rubrics have been prioritized according to their frequency and then homogenized to correspond to the following categories: economy, health, international, culture, regional and sport. Existing categories with unambiguous meanings such as âfeuilletonâ, âletzte seiteâ etc. as well as rubrics that corresponded more to headlines were set to NA in order to be classified anew by the machine learning algorithm. By means of Râs library RTextTools, a support vector machine algorithm was trained on the articles with valid rubrics and was then used to predict the respective rubricâs category for the articles with no rubric, based on the text of the article. This categorization was only conducted for the sample of german articles as the sample size for the french and italian articles were too small to generate a reliable training set for the same categories as in german.

It can be seen, that the economy was the rubric with the most coverage, followed by regional and news about health, international news, culture, sport and finally opinion It is worth mentionning in this context that in many articles, components of more than one rubric are present. It is for example clear that in articles that fall under the rubric âregionalâ or âinternationalâ, several issues are mixed; as such discussions about health and economic issues will certainly be found in the articles sorted into these categories. Nevertheless I believe that this classification may shed some light on the distribution of the subjects in the news coverage about the COVID-19 crisis.

# IN THE END PUT ON EVAL=TRUE!!!!
# train SVM for missing rubrics
matrix.rub <- rbind.data.frame(train.df, predict.df)
doc_matrix <- create_matrix(matrix.rub$content, language="german", 
                            removeNumbers=TRUE,
                            stemWords=TRUE)
container <- create_container(doc_matrix, matrix.rub$rub, trainSize=1:2188,
                              testSize=2189:9761, virgin=FALSE)
SVM <- train_model(container,"SVM")
rub.pred <- classify_model(container, SVM)

# complete missing rubrics into dataset
matrix.rub$rub[2189:9761] <- rub.pred$SVM_LABEL

# plots
p.rub <- data.frame(sort(table(matrix.rub$rub), decreasing=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x=reorder(Var1, Freq), y=Freq)) +
  geom_col() + 
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() + theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(x="", y="", title = "Distribution of rubrics in german articles")

p.rub.month.prop <- data.frame(table(matrix.rub$month, matrix.rub$rub))%>%
  filter(., Var1 != "2022-06-01") %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x=Var1, group=Var2)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=Freq, col=Var2)) +
  theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "none", 
                          axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, size=6),
                          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(x="", y="", title = "Salience of rubrics over time in german articles") +
  facet_wrap(~Var2)


When plotting the development of the rubrics against a time axis, the importance of the rubrics in relation to each other and the changes of the salience of the subjects can be observed. In the following plot, it can be seen that at the initial stages of the pandemia, coverage about the economy showed the highest salience, which is not surprising when considering that when the first shutdown initiated in mid March 2020 itâs economic consequences were largely unknown. As time moved on and short work compensation and all other measures of financial assistance proved to stabilize Switzerlandâs economy to a considerable extent, the trend of coverage on economic subjects gradually decreased.

When turning to the rubrics of regional, health, international and sport (in order of their realtive importance), it is quite obvious that the salience of these subjects correlates more or less with the virulence of the spread of the infections over the course of time. The initial hump in spring 2020 was succeeded by a slight recovery in summer 2020, followed by a strong rise in autumn 2020 that peaked in winter 2021. The decrease in spring/summer 2021 was then followed by a continuous increase during the last autumn with another peak in winter 2021/2022 and a gradual decrease until recent times.

With the rubrics culture and opinion it looks like the salience peaked around the initial stages of the pandemia with a gradual decrease in coverage over the next two years, accompanied by some variance.

These observations show, that a categorization into rubrics can be useful in assessing the relative importance of particular subjects. Furthermore, the salience of these subjects can be retraced over time which can in turn be put into context with real life events.

Sentiment Analysis

In this section, the degree of emotionalization of articles will be scrutinized. For this purpose, sentiment dictionaries from Kaggle were downloaded. This repository provides lexicons for sentiment analysis in 81 languages.

To produce a comparable measure for the degree of emotionalization, positive and negative tokens were added and divided through the word count for each article. The resulting variable signifies emotional notions as a share of the total words per article and can thus be interpreted as an indicator for the degree of emotionalization. This indicator was then aggregated over media types and is displayed on a time axis in the charts below. As the articles in italian originated 100% from SRG Online, obviously no comparison between media type with respect to the degree of emotionalization can be conducted.

The chart below shows that for german, articles that were published in a tabloid medium show the highest share of emotional words. In contrast, news from SRG Online show the lowest level of emotionalization. It is worth noting that articles from the commuter press show quite a high degree of variance when compared to other media types. Magazines and the subscription press show intermediate levels of emotionalization. All medium types include printed press as well as online content (except SRG Online of course). The medium type âotherâ consists of a few articles only and is therefore not interpreted. In the table below the chart, pairwise t-tests are reported between the average level of emotionalization of the subscription press as a basline category in comparison with tabloids, the commuter press, SRG online and magazines. Results show, that the tabloid press shows the mighest mean, that is statistically significantly distinguishable from the mean of subscription press. SRG Online shows the lowest mean and itâs difference is statistically significant from subscription press as well. A bit as a surprise comes the fact, that commuter press and magazines show the same value for the average degree of emotionalization; both of these means are statistically not destinguishable from the mean of emotionalization in the subscription press on a 5% confidence level.

T-Tests of emotionalization per media type vs.Â subscriptions in german articles
Media Type Mean Mean Subscribtions p-Value
Tabloid 0.812% 0.750% 0.0004853
Commuter Press 0.722% 0.750% 0.3494421
SRG Online 0.661% 0.750% 0.0000006
Magazine 0.718% 0.750% 0.0389275

For french articles, variance is generally higher than for german articles which is due to less observations/articles in the sample as can be seen on the following chart. Also here, the tabloid press shows the highest level of emotionalization, but the t-test for a comparison with the mean of the subscription press does not produce a statistically significant value. Again as with german articles, SRG Online shows the lowest level of emotionalization and itâs mean is statistically significantly different from subscription press. Also here, the level of emotionalization in the commuter press is lower than in the subscription press and produces a statistically significant p-value.

T-Tests of emotionalization per media type vs.Â subscriptions in french articles
Media Type Mean Mean Subscribtions p-Value
Tabloid 0.826% 0.800% 0.3718010
Commuter Press 0.724% 0.800% 0.0000642
SRG Online 0.690% 0.800% 0.0005398
Magazine 0.804% 0.800% 0.9387386

All in all it can be said, that SRG Online articles in the sample show the lowest share of emotional notions when compared to other media types, which could be interpreted as a more sober style of journalism. This can be observed in german as well as in french articles alike. On the other hand, the tabloid press shows the highest level of emotionalization in both german and french articles, although the mean is statistically reliably distinguishable from subscriptions only in german. A bit as a surprise comes the fact, that articles from the commuter press do not show higher levels of emotionalization than the subscription press; in french articles, the mean share of emotional notions is even significantly lower than in subscription press. This difference between german and french articles might indicate that distinct journalistic cultures might result in different degrees of emotionalization per media type. These results confirm my hypothesis therefore only partly: Tabloid press shows higher levels of emotionalization from subscription press but commuter press does not. This holds for both articles in german and french.

User Reactions in Online Media

To investigate how users interact with articles on online media, an exemplary analysis of the comments of users as well as the reactions of other users to these comments (love/hate buttons) on all articles from the online news site watson.ch that were categorized in the rubric âCoronavirusâ was conducted. As watson.ch does not provide an API for searching itâs archive, all data was scraped manually from the web. To each article, the most popular three user comments were scraped too, along with the user reactions in the form of hits of the love/hate-buttons to this comment. The following code chunk shows the original scraping process and the composition of a dataset, that could be used to further investigate, how user comments and the reactions from other users interact with the original articles.

Show R code 
#https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wlUzEYdC9A3C2z1Xtsw5oeTBb7rHxSfc/view?usp=sharing

url <- "https://www.watson.ch/Coronavirus"
url2 <- "https://www.watson.ch/Coronavirus/?page="
page <- page <- read_html(url)
pages <- page %>% html_nodes(".widget.pagination") %>% html_text()
npages <- max(as.numeric(unlist(regmatches(pages, gregexpr("[[:digit:]]+", pages)))))

links <- list()
temp <- list()
for (i in 1:npages) { #15:13 - 15:15, 83*73: 6059links
  ifelse(i==1,
         temp <- list(read_html(url) %>% html_nodes("a.teaserlink") %>% html_attr("href")),
         temp <- list(read_html(paste(url2, i, sep="")) %>% html_nodes("a.teaserlink") %>% html_attr("href")))
  links <- rbind(links, temp)
}
links <- unlist(links)

articles <- list()
part <- list()
for (i in 1:length(links)) { #15:16 - 19:00
  temp <- read_html(links[i]) %>%
    html_nodes("p") %>% html_text()
  temp <- temp[-length(temp)] # clean from last entry, is from another article
  # bind parts together
  for (j in 1:length(temp)) {
    part <- paste(part, temp[j])
  }
  articles[[i]] <- part
  part <- NULL
} 

dates <- list()
for (i in 1:length(links)) { #19:02 - 22:40
  temp <- read_html(links[i]) %>%
    html_nodes(".mb-8") %>% html_text()
  # date either in paragraph 1 or 2, if not then ignore
  try({ 
    x <- ifelse(gregexpr("[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]", temp[1])[[1]][1] != "-1",
              substr(temp[1],
                     (gregexpr("[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]", temp[1])[[1]][1]),
                     (gregexpr("[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]", temp[1])[[1]][1]+9)),
              substr(temp[2],
                     (gregexpr("[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]", temp[2])[[1]][1]),
                     (gregexpr("[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9].[0-9][0-9][0-9][0-9]", temp[2])[[1]][1]+9)))
  dates[[i]] <- as.Date(paste(substr(x, nchar(x)-3, nchar(x)),
                substr(x, nchar(x)-6, nchar(x)-5),
                substr(x, nchar(x)-9, nchar(x)-8),
                sep="-"))
  })
}

comments <- list() # 06:42 - vorauss. 09:30
for (i in 1:length(links)) {
  temp <- read_html(links[i]) %>%
    html_nodes(".mb-2.watson-snippet__text") %>% html_text()
  comments[[i]] <- temp
}

reactions.love <- list()
for (i in 1:length(links)) {
  temp <- read_html(links[i]) %>%
    html_nodes(".vote_love") %>% html_text()
  reactions.love[[i]] <- temp
}

reactions.hate <- list()
for (i in 1:length(links)) {
  temp <- read_html(links[i]) %>%
    html_nodes(".vote_hate") %>% html_text()
  reactions.hate[[i]] <- temp
}

# compose data.frame
watson <- data.frame(matrix(nrow = length(articles)))
watson$article <- unlist(articles)
watson$date <- as.Date(as.numeric(matrix(unlist(purrr::map_depth(dates, 1, ~ifelse(is.null(.x), NA, .x) )
))), origin = "1970-01-01")

for (i in 1:length(articles)) {
  watson$comment1[i] <- unlist(comments[[i]])[1]
  watson$comment2[i] <- unlist(comments[[i]])[2]
  watson$comment3[i] <- unlist(comments[[i]])[3]
  watson$love1[i] <- as.numeric(unlist(reactions.love[[i]])[1])
  watson$love2[i] <- as.numeric(unlist(reactions.love[[i]])[2])
  watson$love3[i] <- as.numeric(unlist(reactions.love[[i]])[3])
  watson$hate1[i] <- as.numeric(unlist(reactions.hate[[i]])[1])
  watson$hate2[i] <- as.numeric(unlist(reactions.hate[[i]])[2])
  watson$hate3[i] <- as.numeric(unlist(reactions.hate[[i]])[3])
}

watson$love_to_hate1 <- ifelse(is.na(watson$hate1) == TRUE, 0, (watson$love1-watson$hate1)/(watson$hate1+watson$love1))
watson$love_to_hate2 <- ifelse(is.na(watson$hate2) == TRUE, 0, (watson$love2-watson$hate2)/(watson$hate2+watson$love2))
watson$love_to_hate3 <- ifelse(is.na(watson$hate3) == TRUE, 0, (watson$love3-watson$hate3)/(watson$hate3+watson$love3))

watson$char <- nchar(watson$article)

#cleaning
watson <- watson[!is.na(watson$date),]
watson <- watson[watson$date > "2020-01-01",]

Not all articles were opened for user comments. Non-commented articles were thus eliminated from the sample. The dataset was then used to produce a corpus, which was tokenized (data cleaning was mainly conducted during the scraping process). On the articles themselves as well as on the first comment with the most user reactions, a sentiment analysis was conducted. This produced counts for positive/negative notions per article and per comment. From these figures, the ratio of net positive notions from total notions was calculated (positive - negative) / (positive + pegative) for the content of the article as well as for the first comment. For the hits of love/hate buttons, the net positive user reactions ratio is calculated in the same way (love - hate) / (love + hate). Positive values of these variables indicate that positive notions outweigh negatives in all sentiment notions; as the variable is calculated as a share of total notions, it represents a relative value that can be compared over articles, although it must be mentioned that this procedure eliminates different intensities of notions over different articles.

Show R code 
watson <- readRDS(file = "watson.rds")

corp_watson <- corpus(watson, text_field = "article")

tok_watson <- tokens(corp_watson, 
                 remove_separators = TRUE,
                 include_docvars = TRUE,
                 remove_punct = T)

tok_watson <- tokens_remove(tok_watson, c("dass", "00", "sei", "seit", "imm", "ab", "beim", "+", "frank"))

tok_watson <- tok_watson %>% 
  tokens_tolower %>%  
  tokens_remove(stopwords(kind = "german")) %>% 
  tokens_wordstem(language = "german") %>%
  tokens_remove("")

dfm_watson <- dfm(tok_watson)

mydfm_watson_sent.dfm %<>%
  convert(to = "data.frame") %>%
  left_join(mydfm_watson_sent.dfm.dv)

mydfm_watson_sent.dfm %<>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::floor_date(date, "month")) %>%
  mutate(bal = pos - neg)

# group by month
sent_watson <- mydfm_watson_sent.dfm %>%
  select(pos, neg, month) %>%
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarize_all(sum) %>%
  mutate(bal = pos - neg) %>%
  mutate(pos_to_neg = (pos - neg) / (pos + neg))


## sentiment analysis on comments
corp_watson_comment1 <- corpus(watson, text_field = "comment1")

tok_watson_comment1 <- tokens(corp_watson_comment1, 
                     remove_separators = TRUE,
                     include_docvars = TRUE,
                     remove_punct = T)

tok_watson_comment1 <- tokens_remove(tok_watson_comment1, c("dass", "00", "sei", "seit", "imm", "ab", "beim", "+", "frank"))

tok_watson_comment1 <- tok_watson_comment1 %>% 
  tokens_tolower %>%  
  tokens_remove(stopwords(kind = "german")) %>% 
  tokens_wordstem(language = "german") %>%
  tokens_remove("")

dfm_watson_comment1 <- dfm(tok_watson_comment1)

toks_watson_sent_comment1 <- 
  tokens_lookup(tok_watson_comment1, 
                dictionary =  de_sent) 

mydfm_watson_sent_comment1 <- dfm(toks_watson_sent_comment1)
mydfm_watson_sent_comment1.dfm <- dfm(toks_watson_sent_comment1)
mydfm_watson_sent_comment1.dfm.dv <- docvars(corp_watson_comment1) %>%
  mutate(doc_id = paste("text", rownames(.), sep = ""))

#join to main watson df
mydfm_watson_sent_comment1.dfm %<>% # attention! this is the "assign and update" pipe!
  convert(to = "data.frame") %>%
  left_join(mydfm_watson_sent.dfm.dv)
mydfm_watson_sent_comment1.dfm %<>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::floor_date(date, "month")) %>%
  mutate(bal = pos - neg)

# map sentiment indicators of comment1 to main watson df
df_temp <- mydfm_watson_sent_comment1.dfm %>%
  select(doc_id, pos, neg)
colnames(df_temp) <- c("doc_id", "pos_c1", "neg_c1")
watson_c1 <- mydfm_watson_sent.dfm %>% 
  left_join(df_temp)

# watson_c1$char_c1 <- nchar(watson_c1$comment1) #is this needed?!

# INTERACTION 1st stage: a pos comment on a pos article is reinforcing, a neg comment on a pos article is contradicting
watson_c1 %<>% mutate(interact1 = ((pos - neg) / (pos + neg)) * ((pos_c1 - neg_c1) / (pos_c1 + neg_c1)))

watson_c1 %<>% 
  mutate(pos_to_neg = (pos - neg) / (pos + neg)) %<>%
  mutate(pos_to_neg_c1 = (pos_c1 - neg_c1) / (pos_c1 + neg_c1)) %<>%
  mutate(love_to_hate_c1 = (love1 - hate1) / (love1 + hate1))

p.corr1 <- ggplot(watson_c1, aes(x=pos_to_neg, y=pos_to_neg_c1)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(alpha = 0.1), size = 1, width = 0.05, height = 0.05) +
  geom_smooth() +
  theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "none", 
                          plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(x="Net pos. sentiment ratio of article",
       y="Net pos. sentiment ratio of first comment", 
       title = "First comments vs. articles")

corr1 <- cor(watson_c1$pos_to_neg, watson_c1$pos_to_neg_c1, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")
fit1.1 <- lm(data =  watson_c1, pos_to_neg_c1 ~ pos_to_neg)
fit1.2 <- lm(data =  watson_c1, pos_to_neg_c1 ~ pos_to_neg + as.factor(month)) 

# INTERACTION 2nd stage: love reactions on a pos comment is reinforcing, hate reactions on a pos comment is contradicting
p.corr2 <- ggplot(watson_c1, aes(x=pos_to_neg_c1, y=love_to_hate_c1)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(alpha = 0.1), size = 1, width = 0.05, height = 0.05) +
  geom_smooth() +
  theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "none",

  labs(x="Net pos. sentiment ratio of first comment", 
       y="Net positive user reactions ratio to first comment",

When visualizing the relation between the net positive sentiment ratio of the article and the net positive sentiment ratio of the first comment, a positive relationship can be observed. This means that on average user comments reinforce the sentimental tilt of the article. This is shown in the left chart below. In the right chart, the relation between the net positive sentiment ratio of the comments and the net positive user reactions ratio is visualized. Here, the relationship between the two variables is not so straight forward.

The above plotted relationships are analyzed a bit more thoroughly by means of linear regression. Models 1 and 2 represent the first stage of interaction of users with the content of the articles on watson.ch and regress the net positive sentiment ratio of articles onto the net positive sentiment ratio of the first comments, where the second model includes monthly fixed effects. In models 1 and 2, results show that higher values of a net positive ratio in 1st comments are positively and significantly associated with higher values of net positive ratios in the original articles. In other words: The higher the net positive ratio of the article, the higher the net positive ratio of the comments. The positive and significant coefficient for the constant shows that there a baseline-support in the comments could be present. The inclusion of monthly dummies as period fixed-effects in model 2 does not change this relationship but the level of the baseline-support, which turns slightly negative. It is worth mentioning, that all monthly dummy variables produce positive and significant coefficients in model 2 (not shown in table). Additionaly, including monthly fixed effexts increases the explanatory power of the model quite considerably as can be seen from the adjusted R^2 statistics. These aspects indicate, that user reactions to articles varied over time and that this variation should be taken into account when interpreting the relationship between the articles net positive sentiment ratio and the respective measure of the first comments.

Models 3 and 4 show the second stage of interaction where users react to users comments by hitting the like or hate buttons respectively and regress the net positive sentiment ratio of first comments onto the net positive user reaction on the first comment, also with monthly fixed effects in model 4. As can be seen in the plot above, the relationship does not appear to be of a linear form but shows more the characteristic U-shape of a quadratic relationship. Models 3 and 4âs main predictor is then modeled as a quadratic term, for which the estimated coefficient is also positive and significant, which confirms the non-linear relationship between usersâ reactions on usersâ comments. The baseline-support as measured by the intercept shows a quite high positive and significant value in both models. Contrary to model 2, the inclusion of monthy dummy variables does not change the level of the constant and hardly any of the coefficients of these period fixed effects are statistically significant (not shown in table). Taken together, a possible interpretation of these figures could be that comments that follow a more sober style of communication (low level of emotionalization) generate higher levels of affirmation than comments with a medium level of emotionalization; with comments that show high shares of emotional terms, affirmation by user reactions rises again.

Conclusion

In the above analysis I have examplarily shown on the subject of the COVID-19 pandemia, that there is evidence that different media types show on average different levels of emotionalization when reporting on the same subject. The results suggest furthermore that there may be different journalistic cultures in Switzerlandâs national languages that are reflected in different average levels of emotionalization of media types between german and french articles. When turning to online media content that allows for user interaction - in the above analysis exemplarily conducted with all articles on the COVID-19 pandemic on watson.ch - it can be shown, that on average user reinforce an articlesâ degree of emotionalization when commenting on it. User reacting on usersâ comments show a different association: Affirmation level is high for comments with a sober style (low level of emotionalization), low for medium levels of emotionalization and high again for emotionally opinionated comments. Although the analysis on user interactions with online news produces some interesting insights, further research is needed to validate these findings in a broader setting. These initial analysis may therefore serve as a starting point to generate more accurate hypothesis that can be tested in a carefully reflected research design.
